[{"sha":"bf41e8f123772983b63fa78102d06bf8e0c0071e","author":{"email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com","name":"Justin Lebar"},"message":"Make printConvolutionDimensions handle "unknown" dimensions.

In XLA:GPU, the dimensions in ConvDimensionNumbersAttr need not be "dense".
For example, we could have spatial dimensions [0,2], batch dimension [3], and
feature dimension [4].  In this case, dimension [1] is "unknown".

This is used for the VECT_C dimension in cudnn convolutions.

XLA's ConvolutionDimensionNumbers struct already handles this; see
ConvolutionDimensionNumbersToString().

[{"sha":"c41e88b59209906b224c879a1e20db65d97c65fb","author":{"email":"ed153eb53cb1ee65f26e4e5e01d07866259e5413@google.com","name":"Shilpa Krish"},"message":"Use the cached finalized_dataset in DatasetBase when finalizing during sequential access.

This fixes GitHub issue #53292 in which tf.data.experimental.load() did not work with temporary datasets even after caching the dataset. Before this change, dataset finalization (which allows options to propagate through datasets) was performed each time an iterator for a dataset was created.  When finalizing a cached LoadDataset, an error was thrown if the underlying file was no longer present. This would occur if the saved file had been in a temporary directory and the temporary directory was now out of scope. This CL fixes the issue by performing finalization only the first time an iterator for a dataset is created. Subsequent iterations use a cached version of the finalized dataset rather than performing the finalization again.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/53292

read-only files. This is not adding a lot of value, and the two
tests do not act correctly when the executing user is root, as is
common on CI environments, especially with Docker.

Instead of disabling the two targets, Mihai and I think that the
value of these testcases is quite low and they can be removed.

[{"sha":"43abc0fea0a755395a9c968dbb64170e2cdfdb0b","author":{"email":"d4bfa6cff7deeb2d212f12b0b03668d8e8509321@google.com","name":"Anish Tondwalkar"},"message":"Turn on SwapConvOperands on gpu

This swaps operands in cases in which doing so would bring significant performance benefits (e.g. for filters with large paddings). It's not guaranteed that the swap can be lowered to cudnn, however, so we must check that gpu_conv_rewriter can make sense of the new conv before replacing the old conv with it.
